cs.GT, cs.DS, cs.CC, cs.EC, cs.NE 

The paper deals with the problem of computing market equilibria, which is a central topic in game theory and economics. The use of Leontief economies and Scarf's fixed-point approximation algorithm are also strong indicators that the paper belongs to the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. The analysis of the smoothed complexity suggests that the paper could also be relevant to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. The use of approximation algorithms and the connection to PPAD (Polynomial Parity Arguments on Directed graphs) also suggest that the paper could be relevant to the cs.EC (Economics and Computation) and cs.NE (Networks and Economics) sub-categories.
